"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043051","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-01-24","<p>We continue to advocate actively for the inclusion of women in the Yemeni peace process and encourage political actors to take women’s views into account. Through the Conflict, Stability and Security Fund (CSSF) we support projects with UN Women which aim to increase Yemeni women’s capacity to influence political/conflict actors and the peace process, including through the Yemeni Women Pact. CSSF projects also support the inclusion of women in Track II political dialogue, and in local peacebuilding initiatives. During last month’s peace talks in Stockholm, UN Special Envoy Martin Griffiths invited eight women, representing different political parties, civil society, activists and development workers in Yemen, to assist him during negotiations. Our Embassy also used our social media accounts in the run up to Stockholm to encourage the parties to include women in their delegations.</p><p>​</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2019-01-24T17:04:53.383Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043051/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043051/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043051/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-01-17","Yemen: Peace Negotiations","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what assessment he has made of the merits of participation by women’s organisations in the UN-led peace consultations on Yemen.","false","Biography information for Stephen Twigg","Liverpool, West Derby","Stephen Twigg","209735"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043052","Scotland Office","false","2019-01-21","<p>I currently have no plans to visit a food bank in my capacity as Secretary of State for Scotland in February 2019.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2019-01-21T10:31:14.217Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043052/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043052/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043052/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2019-01-17","Food Banks: Scotland","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, whether he plans to visit a food bank in February 2019.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","209857"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043053","Department for International Trade","false","2019-01-25","<p>The highest hourly rate paid by the Department for International Trade for external legal advice in 2018 was £816ph. This was for a piece of urgent foreign law advice for which it was not possible to use the usual Government Legal Services Panels. The advice was subject to an overall fee cap and only 4.4 hours was charged at the £816 hourly rate.</p><p> </p><p>The Department for International Trade does not currently have any arms-length bodies.</p>","Meon Valley","George Hollingbery",,"2019-01-25T16:24:02.953Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043053/answer","Biography information for Sir George Hollingbery","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043053/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043053/answer",,,,,"202","International Trade","International Trade","2019-01-17","Department for International Trade: Legal Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for International Trade, what the highest hourly rate was that (a) his Department and (b) each of his Department's arms-length bodies paid for legal advice in 2018.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","209810"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043054","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-01-22","<p>NHS England set clinical commissioning group (CCG) allocations. The National Health Service published draft five-year CCG allocations for 2019/20 to 2023/24 on 10 January 2019 at the following link:</p><p> </p><p><a href="https://www.england.nhs.uk/publication/draft-ccg-allocations-2019-20-to-2023-24-core-services/" target="_blank">https://www.england.nhs.uk/publication/draft-ccg-allocations-2019-20-to-2023-24-core-services/</a></p><p> </p><p>These are subject to final approval by the NHS England Board on 31 January 2019.</p>","Wimbledon","Stephen Hammond",,"2019-01-22T17:04:07.083Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043054/answer","Biography information for Stephen Hammond","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043054/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043054/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-01-17","NHS: Finance","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, pursuant to his oral contribution of 7 January 2019, Official Report column 80, when he plans to publish the local provision funding increases for the first year of the NHS Long Term Plan.","false","Biography information for Paul Farrelly","Newcastle-under-Lyme","Paul Farrelly","209758"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043055","Department for Transport","false","2019-01-25","<p>The Department consists of the central Department and four executive Agencies as follows:</p><p> </p><p>Driver and Vehicle Licensing Agency (DVLA)</p><p>Driver and Vehicle Standards Agency (DVSA)</p><p>Maritime and Coastguard Agency (MCA)</p><p>Vehicle Certification Agency (VCA)</p><p><strong> </strong></p><p>The highest hourly rate that the Department paid for legal advice in 2018 is £640.00.</p><p> </p><p>The highest hour rate that each of the Department’s arms-length bodies paid for legal advice in 2018 as follows:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Highways England</p></td><td><p>£360.00</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Transport Focus</p></td><td><p>£350.00</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>British Transport Police Authority</p></td><td><p>£400.00</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Northern Lighthouse Board</p></td><td><p>£250.00</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Trinity House Lighthouse Service</p></td><td><p>£400.00</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>High Speed 2 Ltd</p></td><td><p>£446.74</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Network Rail</p></td><td><p>£690.00</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Hereford and South Herefordshire","Jesse Norman",,"2019-01-25T13:42:38.31Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043055/answer","Biography information for Jesse Norman","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043055/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043055/answer",,,,,"27","Transport","Transport","2019-01-17","Department for Transport: Legal Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Transport, what the highest hourly rate was that (a) his Department and (b) each of his Department's arms-length bodies paid for legal advice in 2018.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","209811"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043056","Department for Work and Pensions","false","2019-01-23","<p>The information requested is not in the public domain due to it being commercially sensitive and should not be disclosed. If disclosed it would be likely to impact the commercial interests of the Department and arms-length bodies, and the ability to obtain goods and services on the best possible commercial terms.</p>","North Swindon","Justin Tomlinson",,"2019-01-23T10:16:05.597Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043056/answer","Biography information for Justin Tomlinson","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043056/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043056/answer",,,,,"29","Work and Pensions","Work and Pensions","2019-01-17","Department for Work and Pensions: Legal Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Work and Pensions, what the highest hourly rate was that (a) her Department and (b) each of her Department's arms-length bodies paid for legal advice in 2018.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","209812"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043057","Department of Health and Social Care","false","2019-01-25","<p>The Government Legal Department (GLD) provides almost all of the Department’s legal services. The largest components are for general advisory and commercial advisory work. The Department pays for both of these on a fixed fee basis, and therefore hourly rates are not applicable for these areas of legal work.</p><p>Hourly rates do apply where employment advisory and litigation work is provided by the GLD. In 2018, the highest hourly rate paid for such legal services was £180 for a Queen’s Counsel.</p><p>It is only where specific legal advice is required that specialist firms of solicitors provide services for the Department, and these are engaged with the guidance of the GLD.</p><p>The Department’s arm’s length bodies (ALBs) each have their own arrangements for securing legal services. The following table sets out the highest hourly rates for legal services in 2018 that ALBs paid.</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p>Name</p></td><td><p>Amount</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Care Quality Commission</p></td><td><p>£280</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Health Education England</p></td><td><p>£250</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Health Research Authority</p></td><td><p>£200</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Human Fertilisation and Embryology Authority</p></td><td><p>£350</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Medicines and Healthcare Products Regulatory Agency</p></td><td><p>£180</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>NHS Blood and Transplant</p></td><td><p>£200</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>NHS Business Services Authority</p></td><td><p>£145</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>NHS Counter Fraud Authority</p></td><td><p>£228</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>NHS Digital</p></td><td><p>£280</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>NHS Improvement</p></td><td><p>£250</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>NHS Resolution</p></td><td><p>£250</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>National Institute for Health and Care Excellence</p></td><td><p>£200</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Public Health England</p></td><td><p>£222</p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>The Department and two of its bodies, NHS England and the Human Tissue Authority, have engaged legal services from organisations other than the GLD. It has not been possible in these instances to provide the information requested as it could only be obtained at disproportionate cost.</p><p><strong> </strong></p>","Gosport","Caroline Dinenage",,"2019-01-25T14:18:27.287Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043057/answer","Biography information for Caroline Dinenage","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043057/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043057/answer",,,,,"17","Health and Social Care","Health and Social Care","2019-01-17","Department of Health and Social Care: Legal Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Health and Social Care, what the highest hourly rate was that (a) his Department and (b) each of his Department's arms-length bodies paid for legal advice in 2018.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","209813"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043058","Ministry of Defence","true","2019-01-24","<p>The highest hourly rate paid for legal advice by the Ministry of Defence (MOD) was £<del class="ministerial">580.</del><ins class="ministerial">597.</ins></p><p> </p><p>The highest hourly rate paid for legal advice by the MOD’s arms length bodies is:</p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>Name of Arms Length Body</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Highest Rate</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Defence Electronics and Components Agency</p></td><td><p>£295</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Defence Science and Technology Laboratory</p></td><td><p>£148</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>National Army Museum</p></td><td><p>£550</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>National Museum of the Royal Navy</p></td><td><p>£580</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Oil and Pipelines</p></td><td><p>£250</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Royal Air Force Museum</p></td><td><p>£280</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Royal Hospital Chelsea</p></td><td><p>£530</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Single Source Regulations Office</p></td><td><p>£450</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>United Kingdom Hydrographic Office</p></td><td><p>£675</p></td></tr></tbody></table>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood",,"2019-01-24T16:35:44.157Z","2019-03-28T17:00:18.367Z","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043058/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043058/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043058/answer","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043058/answer/previousversion/97151","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","11","Defence","Defence","2019-01-17","Ministry of Defence: Legal Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, what the highest hourly rate paid for legal advice was by (a) his Department and (b) each of his Department's arms length bodies in 2018.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","209814"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043059","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-01-30","<p>a. <strong>Main Department</strong></p><p>The highest hourly rate that the main Department paid for legal advice in 2018 was £165 excluding VAT. Where the Department has sought advice from counsel, Attorney General’s Office rates will apply. For external legal firms on the General Legal Advice Services (GLAS) panel, rates are agreed under the framework.</p><p> </p><p>b. <strong>Arm’s Length Bodies (ALBs)</strong></p><p> </p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>ALBs</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>ALB’s Highest Hourly Rate 2018 Legal Advise (ex-VAT)</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>ARB (Architects Registration Board)</p></td><td><p>Commercially sensitive</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>BRAC (Building Advisory Committee)</p></td><td><p>NIL. Not Applicable</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>EDC (Ebbsfleet Development Corporation)</p></td><td><p>£250</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>HE (Homes England)</p></td><td><p>Commercially sensitive</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>LEASE (Leasehold Advisory Service)</p></td><td><p>NIL paid</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>LGSCO (Local Government &amp; Social Care Ombudsman)</p></td><td><p>£190</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>PINS (The Planning Inspectorate)</p></td><td><p>£123</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>QEIIC (Queen Elizabeth II Centre)</p></td><td><p>£445</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>VTS (Valuation Tribunal Service)</p></td><td><p>£164</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>RSH (Regulator of Social Housing)</p></td><td><p>Commercially sensitive</p></td></tr><tr><td><p>THO (The Housing Ombudsman)</p></td><td><p>£260</p></td></tr><tr><td><p> </p></td><td><p> </p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p><p>Three of our Arms–Length Bodies (ALB) did not disclose a figure due to commercial sensitivities. The highest hourly rate was that for the QEIIC who were engaged to provide specialist commercial advice on employment legislation. The rate quoted was for the Director who was only engaged for part of the project. The differences in hourly rates across the other ALBs reflects the degree of specialisms.</p><p> </p>","Rossendale and Darwen","Jake Berry",,"2019-01-30T17:46:46.867Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043059/answer","Biography information for Jake Berry","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043059/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043059/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-01-17","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government: Legal Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, what the highest hourly rate was that (a) his Department and (b) each of his Department's arms-length bodies paid for legal advice in 2018.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","209815"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043060","Department for Education","false","2019-01-23","<p>Ofsted does not grade the Army Foundation College in Harrogate on the same basis as civilian colleges for the age group.</p>","Guildford","Anne Milton",,"2019-01-23T15:30:08.417Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043060/answer","Biography information for Anne Milton","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043060/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043060/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-01-17","Army Foundation College","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether Ofsted grades the Army Foundation College in Harrogate on the same basis as civilian colleges for the age group.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","209858"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043061","Home Office","false","2019-01-23","<p>Unfortunately the letter of 27 November was not received until 17 December 2018, when the MP sent an email asking for an update. It is unclear what happened to the original letter and no trace has been found. A response was sent on 15 January 2019. The reply has today been resent to the MP by email and receipt confirmed by the MPs office.</p>","Romsey and Southampton North","Caroline Nokes",,"2019-01-23T15:21:58.45Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043061/answer","Biography information for Caroline Nokes","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043061/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043061/answer",,,,,"1","Home Office","Home Office","2019-01-17","Members: Correspondence","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for the Home Department, when the Minister of State for Immigration plans to respond to the letter from the hon. Member for Glasgow East of 27 November 2018, reference DL2002.","false","Biography information for David Linden","Glasgow East","David Linden","209859"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043062","Ministry of Defence","false","2019-01-24","<p>The Ministry of Defence's Management of Health and Safety Regulations requires special attention to identifying and controlling health and safety risks to young persons in the workplace. Many of these are covered by existing risk assessment and control measures, but the employing branch will identify any additional control measures/changes required in accordance with the normal risk assessment process.</p><p>All Armed Forces personnel are trained for a wide range of operational tasks and environments, including combat. Established procedures are in place to ensure that Service personnel under the age of 18 are not deployed on operations. Our policies on under 18s in Service are robust and comply with national and international law.</p><p>Commanding Officers take their responsibilities towards their personnel extremely seriously. Commanding Officers pay close attention to the needs of under 18s as they pass from recruitment through Phase 1 and Phase 2 training, to operational units.</p>","Bournemouth East","Mr Tobias Ellwood","210553","2019-01-24T16:25:25.533Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043062/answer","Biography information for Mr Tobias Ellwood","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043062/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043062/answer",,,,,"11","Defence","Defence","2019-01-17","Armed Forces: Conditions of Employment","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Defence, which activities undertaken by under-18s in the armed forces constitutes hazardous work as defined under Article 3 (d) of ILO Convention 182 and its accompanying Recommendation 190.","false","Biography information for Liz Saville Roberts","Dwyfor Meirionnydd","Liz Saville Roberts","209860"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043063","Northern Ireland Office","false","2019-01-22","<p>The Northern Ireland Office uses legal services from a variety of providers, however the information requested is not separately recorded. To provide this information would incur disproportionate cost.</p><p>The Northern Ireland Office has three executive non-departmental public bodies – the Northern Ireland Human Rights Commission, the Independent Reporting Commission and the Parades Commission for Northern Ireland; and one advisory non-departmental public body – the Boundary Commission for Northern Ireland. As these bodies are independent of Government, the hon Member may wish to write to the Commissions directly on these matters – contact details are set out below:</p><table><tbody><tr><td><p><strong>ALB</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Status</strong></p></td><td><p><strong>Contact Details</strong></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Parades Commission for Northern Ireland</p></td><td><p><strong>Executive NDPB</strong></p></td><td><p><a href="mailto:info@paradescommission.org" target="_blank">info@paradescommission.org</a></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Independent Reporting Commission</p></td><td><p><strong>Executive NDPB</strong></p></td><td><p><a href="mailto:enquiries@IRCommission.org" target="_blank">enquiries@IRCommission.org</a></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Northern Ireland Human Rights Commission</p></td><td><p><strong>Executive NDPB</strong></p></td><td><p><a href="mailto:information@nihrc.org" target="_blank">information@nihrc.org</a></p></td></tr><tr><td><p>Boundary Commission for Northern Ireland</p></td><td><p><strong>Advisory NDPB</strong></p></td><td><p><a href="mailto:contact@boundarycommission.org.uk" target="_blank">contact@boundarycommission.org.uk</a></p></td></tr></tbody></table><p> </p>","Weston-super-Mare","John Penrose",,"2019-01-22T11:18:54.787Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043063/answer","Biography information for John Penrose","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043063/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043063/answer",,,,,"21","Northern Ireland","Northern Ireland","2019-01-17","Northern Ireland Office: Legal Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Northern Ireland, what the highest hourly rate was that (a) her Department and (b) each of her Department's arms-length bodies paid for legal advice in 2018.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","209816"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043064","Scotland Office","false","2019-01-24","<p>The Office of the Advocate General provides any necessary legal advice to the Office of the Secretary of State for Scotland and its arms-length bodies.</p>","Dumfriesshire, Clydesdale and Tweeddale","David Mundell",,"2019-01-24T09:46:08.93Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043064/answer","Biography information for David Mundell","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043064/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043064/answer",,,,,"2","Scotland","Scotland","2019-01-17","Scotland Office: Legal Costs","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Scotland, what the highest hourly rate paid for legal advice was by (a) his Department and (b) each of his Department's arms length bodies in 2018.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","209817"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043065","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-01-22","<p>The information requested is provided in the attached table.</p><p> </p><p>MMPR has been implemented in all Young Offender Institutions and Secure Training Centres since summer 2017. It is specifically developed for use by staff working with young people in custody, to avoid physical restraint as far as possible by using a range of de-escalation, diversion and behaviour management techniques to help deal with issues effectively and appropriately.</p><p> </p><p>The safety and wellbeing of all children in our care is our top priority which is why we are reforming youth custody to reduce violence and improve outcomes for children and young people.</p>","Charnwood","Edward Argar",,"2019-01-22T17:12:30.323Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043065/answer","Biography information for Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043065/answer","PQ209818 - MMPR By Reason and Establishment.xlsx","209818 - MMPR by reason and establishment","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043065/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-01-17","Secure Accommodation: Restraint Techniques","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, on how many occasions Minimising and Managing Physical Restraint (MMPR) has been used in each secure institution which uses it in each year for which information is available by reason for the use of MMPR.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","209818"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043066","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-01-22","<p>Such assessments are no longer acceptable for buildings subject to the ban on combustible materials in external walls in regulation 7(3) of the Building Regulations. For buildings outside the scope of the ban such as hotels and offices, the current requirements for limited combustibility or for the whole wall system to have passed a BS 8414 test apply.</p><p>A new standard for assessments relating to the BS 8414 cladding test is currently being drafted.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse","209821 ; 209826","2019-01-22T17:07:15.743Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043066/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043066/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043066/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-01-17","Hotels: Insulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, whether desktop studies can still be used  in lieu of tests as a route to compliance for combustible materials on high-rise hotels.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","209819"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043067","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-01-22","<p>The information requested is provided in the attached table.</p><p> </p><p>The safety of children in custody is our top priority. That is why we are reforming youth custody, to reduce violence and improve outcomes for children and young people. This includes rolling out the Custody Support Plan (CuSP), to provide each young person with a personal officer to work with in order to build trust and consistency. We are also introducing a new Youth Justice Specialist role and providing funding for every Prison Officer in the Youth Custody Service to undertake a youth justice qualification. Over 300 frontline staff are currently enrolled on this qualification. In addition, we are expanding frontline staff capacity in public-sector Young Offender Institutions by 20%, and our figures show that, at the end of September 2018, the Youth Custody Service had 239 more frontline officers than at the same time the previous year.</p>","Charnwood","Edward Argar",,"2019-01-22T17:14:26.677Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043067/answer","Biography information for Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043067/answer","PQ 209820 - Self Harm.xlsx","PQ 209820 Self Harm","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043067/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-01-17","Secure Accommodation: Self-harm","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many incidents of self-harm have been recorded in relation to children in each secure institution that holds children during each of the last five years for which information is available.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","209820"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043068","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-01-22","<p>Such assessments are no longer acceptable for buildings subject to the ban on combustible materials in external walls in regulation 7(3) of the Building Regulations. For buildings outside the scope of the ban such as hotels and offices, the current requirements for limited combustibility or for the whole wall system to have passed a BS 8414 test apply.</p><p>A new standard for assessments relating to the BS 8414 cladding test is currently being drafted.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse","209819 ; 209826","2019-01-22T17:07:15.79Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043068/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043068/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043068/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-01-17","Offices: Insulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, whether desktop studies can still be used in lieu of tests as a route to compliance for combustible materials on high-rise offices.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","209821"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043069","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-01-22","<p>Her Majesty’s Prison and Probation Service (HMPPS) do not hold the specific information requested centrally and it could only be obtained at disproportionate cost by manually searching through individual records and logs. HMPPS are, however, in the process of reviewing how segregation data is collected across each establishment in the Youth Estate.</p>","Charnwood","Edward Argar","209823","2019-01-22T17:15:58.203Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043069/answer","Biography information for Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043069/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043069/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-01-17","Secure Accommodation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the average length of time was that a child spent in the segregation unit in each secure institution that holds children in each of the last five years for which information is available.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","209822"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043070","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-01-22","<p>Her Majesty’s Prison and Probation Service (HMPPS) do not hold the specific information requested centrally and it could only be obtained at disproportionate cost by manually searching through individual records and logs. HMPPS are, however, in the process of reviewing how segregation data is collected across each establishment in the Youth Estate.</p>","Charnwood","Edward Argar","209822","2019-01-22T17:15:58.25Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043070/answer","Biography information for Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043070/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043070/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-01-17","Secure Accommodation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, what the longest length of time was that a child spent in the segregation unit in each secure institution that holds children in each of the last five years for which information is available.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","209823"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043071","Ministry of Justice","false","2019-01-25","<p>The information requested is provided in the attached table.</p><p> </p><p>HMPPS are in the process of reviewing how this data is collected across each establishment in the Youth Estate. We are reforming youth custody to reduce violence and improve outcomes for children and young people. Our vision for a distinct service designed around the needs of young people includes staff specifically recruited and trained to work with children, education and healthcare provision that is tailored to need, and specialist units for the most vulnerable.</p>","Charnwood","Edward Argar",,"2019-01-25T10:23:28.897Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043071/answer","Biography information for Edward Argar","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043071/answer","Copy of PQ 209824 - STC Time Out of Room.xlsx","Table","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043071/answer",,,,,"54","Justice","Justice","2019-01-17","Secure Training Centres","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Justice, how many hours on average per day young people spent unlocked from their rooms in each secure training centre in each of the last five years.","false","Biography information for Richard Burgon","Leeds East","Richard Burgon","209824"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043072","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-01-24","<p>Since it came into effect in Hodeidah on 18 December, the fragile ceasefire has continued to hold and there has been a general de-escalation by both sides around the city. We are aware of reports of frontline incidents and skirmishing but these remain low. We urge all parties to support and facilitate the UN’s efforts and to implement the redeployment of forces in Hodeidah as agreed during the Stockholm talks. We welcome the arrival of General Patrick Cammaert, Head of the UN Redeployment Coordination Committee, and welcome the UK-drafted UN Security Council Resolution 2452 establishing a six month UN mission to monitor the Hodeidah ceasefire.</p><p>​</p>","North East Bedfordshire","Alistair Burt",,"2019-01-24T17:06:18.327Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043072/answer","Biography information for Alistair Burt","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043072/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043072/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-01-17","Yemen: Humanitarian Aid","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what recent assessment he has made of the progress on reopening the Sanaa-Hodeidah road in Yemen; and if he will make a statement.","false","Biography information for Stephen Twigg","Liverpool, West Derby","Stephen Twigg","209736"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043073","Department for Education","false","2019-01-25","<p>In the event that the UK leaves the EU with no agreement in place, the government’s underwrite guarantee will cover the payment of awards to UK applicants for all successful Erasmus+ bids submitted before the UK exits the EU.</p><p>Further details are set out in the technical notice published in August 2018. We will provide further advice shortly.</p><p> </p>","Kingswood","Chris Skidmore",,"2019-01-25T14:40:10.393Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043073/answer","Biography information for Chris Skidmore","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043073/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043073/answer",,,,,"60","Education","Education","2019-01-17","Erasmus+ Programme","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Education, whether the Government plans to replace access to funding universities receive from the Erasmus+ programme for UK students undertaking placements abroad before 2020 in the event that the UK leaves the EU on 29 March 2019 without a deal.","false","Biography information for Dr Lisa Cameron","East Kilbride, Strathaven and Lesmahagow","Dr Lisa Cameron","209825"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043074","Ministry of Housing, Communities and Local Government","false","2019-01-22","<p>Such assessments are no longer acceptable for buildings subject to the ban on combustible materials in external walls in regulation 7(3) of the Building Regulations. For buildings outside the scope of the ban such as hotels and offices, the current requirements for limited combustibility or for the whole wall system to have passed a BS 8414 test apply.</p><p>A new standard for assessments relating to the BS 8414 cladding test is currently being drafted.</p>","North West Hampshire","Kit Malthouse","209819 ; 209821","2019-01-22T17:07:15.837Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043074/answer","Biography information for Kit Malthouse","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043074/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043074/answer",,,,,"7","Housing, Communities and Local Government","Housing, Communities and Local Government","2019-01-17","Buildings: Insulation","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Housing, Communities and Local Government, whether systems incorporating combustible materials are still able be approved for use by desktop studies.","false","Biography information for Mr Steve Reed","Croydon North","Mr Steve Reed","209826"
"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043075","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","false","2019-01-22","<p>We have serious concerns about the human rights situation in Xinjiang and the Chinese Government’s deepening crackdown; including credible reports of re-education camps, and widespread surveillance and restrictions targeted at ethnic minorities.</p><p>During China’s Universal Periodic Review at the UN Human Rights Council on 6 November, the UK made a statement which described our concern about the treatment of ethnic minorities in China, including Uyghurs. We issued a specific recommendation, calling on China to implement the recommendations by the UN Committee on the Elimination of Racial Discrimination on Xinjiang, and to allow the UN to monitor the implementation.</p><p>I raised our concerns about Xinjiang with Vice Minister Guo Yezhou during my visit to China on 22 July 2018. The Foreign Secretary also raised our concerns about the region with Chinese State Councillor and Foreign Minister Wang Yi during his visit to China on 30 July 2018.</p><p>​</p>","Cities of London and Westminster","Mark Field",,"2019-01-22T17:29:25.893Z",,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043075/answer","Biography information for Mark Field","http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043075/answer",,,"http://data.parliament.uk/resources/1043075/answer",,,,,"16","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","Foreign and Commonwealth Office","2019-01-17","China: Ethnic Groups","1","House of Commons","To ask the Secretary of State for Foreign and Commonwealth Affairs, what discussions he has had with his Chinese counterpart on reports from the UN Committee on the Elimination of Racial Discrimination on the treatment of Uighur Muslims in Xinjiang.","false","Biography information for Andrew Griffiths","Burton","Andrew Griffiths","209759"
